# Board & Investor Prep

## When to Use
Preparing for board meetings, investor updates, executive committee reviews, advisory board sessions, analyst briefings, or any presentation to governance-level or capital-level audiences. Also use when the principal is asked to contribute a section to a broader board package or when leadership says "the board wants to know about X."

## Key Principle

Board and investor audiences operate at a fundamentally different altitude than operational teams or even senior leadership. They care about three things: **trajectory** (are we winning?), **risk** (what could derail us?), and **capital allocation** (are we spending wisely?). Every word in a board deliverable should map to one of these.

## Board Update Structure

```
BOARD UPDATE
[Business Unit / Product Portfolio] — [Period]

Metadata: Date, Author, Reporting Period, Classification (Board Confidential)

Executive Summary
  - 3-4 sentences max. The entire story at the highest altitude.
  - Lead with the single most important thing: a win, a risk, or a strategic shift.

Strategic Scorecard
  - Table with 4-6 key metrics, each showing: Current | Prior Period | Target | Trend (↑↓→)
  - Metrics should be outcomes, not activities (revenue, adoption, retention, NPS — not sprint velocity)

Portfolio Highlights
  - 2-3 bullet points per product/workstream: what moved, what matters
  - Bold the "so what" — the board doesn't need to know the feature name, they need to know the customer impact

Market & Competitive Position
  - Any competitive developments worth noting (1-2 sentences each)
  - Market trends that affect strategy
  - Win/loss summary if relevant

Risks & Mitigations
  - Top 2-3 risks (not a laundry list)
  - Each risk gets: Description | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation | Owner
  - Be direct about what's real. Boards lose trust when risks are hidden.

Strategic Decisions / Asks
  - Anything requiring board input, approval, or awareness
  - Frame as: "We recommend X because Y. The trade-off is Z."

Forward Look
  - Next quarter priorities (3-5 max)
  - Key milestones and dates
  - Resource or investment needs on the horizon
```

## Investor Update Structure

For investor-facing communications (quarterly updates, fundraising materials, due diligence support):

```
INVESTOR UPDATE — [Period]

Headline Metrics (the 3-4 numbers that define the business)
  - ARR / Revenue
  - Customer count / growth
  - Net retention / churn
  - Key operational metric (e.g., calls for service processed)

Narrative (1 page max)
  - What happened this quarter (wins, milestones, launches)
  - What's working (product-market fit signals, expansion deals)
  - What's challenging (honest, with context — investors respect candor)
  - What's next (upcoming catalysts, strategic priorities)

Financial Summary (if appropriate)
  - Revenue vs. plan
  - Burn rate / runway (if relevant)
  - Key investment areas

Product & Technology Update
  - Major releases and their customer impact
  - Platform/infrastructure milestones
  - Innovation pipeline (without giving away competitive secrets)
```

## Writing Rules for Board/Investor Content

- **Altitude, altitude, altitude.** If you're explaining how a feature works, you're too deep. Explain what it means for the business.
- **Numbers tell the story.** Every slide or section should have at least one quantified metric. "Strong growth" means nothing. "27% YoY growth, adding 43 agencies" means everything.
- **Trends matter more than snapshots.** Show direction: this quarter vs. last, this year vs. last year, actual vs. target.
- **Risks are credibility builders.** A board update with no risks signals either naivety or dishonesty. Include real risks with real mitigations.
- **One page per topic.** Board members are reading 200+ pages of materials across all their commitments. Respect their time ruthlessly.
- **No jargon.** Board members may not know what "CAD" stands for. Spell it out on first use and prefer plain language throughout. "Computer-Aided Dispatch — the software 911 centers use to manage emergency calls" on first mention, then "dispatch software" thereafter.
- **Strategic, not operational.** "We shipped 47 PBIs this sprint" is operational. "We delivered the mobile platform to general availability, enabling officers to run full queries from the field" is strategic.

## Strategic Scorecard Format

6-column table: Metric | Current | Prior | Target | Trend | Notes

Column widths: [2200, 1400, 1400, 1400, 800, 2160] = 9360

Trend indicators:
- **↑** Green text (#1B7A3D) — improving, on/above target
- **→** Amber text (#B8860B) — flat, watch closely
- **↓** Red text (#C62828) — declining, needs attention

Highlight any metric that is significantly above or below target with cell background shading (green or red respectively).

## Risk Table Format

5-column table: Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation | Owner

Column widths: [2800, 1100, 1100, 3060, 1300] = 9360

Likelihood/Impact values: High / Medium / Low
- High/High: Red cell shading
- High/Medium or Medium/High: Yellow cell shading
- Everything else: No shading

## Board vs. Leadership vs. Team — Altitude Guide

| Element | Board Level | Leadership Level | Team Level |
|---------|------------|-----------------|------------|
| Metric example | "ARR grew 18% to $42M" | "Enterprise CAD added 12 agencies this quarter" | "We closed 47 PBIs and shipped v25.1" |
| Risk example | "Key customer concentration risk: top 5 accounts = 30% of revenue" | "Chicago deployment is at risk of delay; mitigation plan in place" | "Chicago UAT blocked on API integration; Kendrick investigating" |
| Win example | "Mobile platform reached GA, opening $8M TAM in field operations" | "Mobile X launched on iOS and Android with 6 agencies in pilot" | "Mobile X v3.2 shipped with offline query support" |
| Ask example | "Requesting $2M incremental investment in cloud infrastructure" | "Need engineering headcount approval for Q3" | "Need 2 sprint cycles allocated to tech debt" |

## Appendix / Backup Slides

Board packages often need an appendix with deeper detail for reference. Structure:

- **Detailed financials** (if the summary raised questions)
- **Customer case studies** (1-pager per key win)
- **Competitive landscape detail** (the full battle card, not the summary)
- **Product roadmap** (high-level, 4-quarter view)
- **Org chart / team updates** (if relevant to the discussion)

These go at the end and are "break glass in case of questions" materials.

## Follow-Up Questions

- What's the specific board meeting agenda — are you presenting or contributing a section?
- What's the board's current temperature on our business unit? (Supportive, scrutinizing, concerned?)
- Are there specific questions or concerns from the last board meeting that need follow-up?
- Should I pull metrics from Jira or other systems to populate the scorecard?
- Is this a standalone update or part of a larger company-wide board package?
- Do you need a presentation deck (pptx) in addition to or instead of a document?
- Are there any topics the CEO or CFO has flagged as "definitely cover this"?
